      "name": "The Soul at Work: From Alienation to Autonomy"
    }
  ],
  "dateModified": "2026-03-03",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-03",
  "description": "Cognitive capitalism is a concept from post-operaismo thinkers — Yann Moulier-Boutang, Carlo Vercellone, and others — describing the phase of capitalism in which knowledge, attention, and affective labor become the primary sources of value. Under cognitive capitalism, the production of ideas, communication, and interpretation is the central economic activity, not a supplement to material production. Value extraction shifts from the factory floor to the nervous system.\nThe concept builds on the operaismo tradition\u0026rsquo;s analysis of how capital reorganizes the labor process across historical phases. Where industrial capitalism extracted value from manual labor disciplined by the assembly line, cognitive capitalism extracts value from mental and relational activity that resists the same forms of measurement and control. The workplace dissolves into life itself: every conversation, every act of attention, every moment of creative problem-solving becomes potentially productive for capital.\n",
  "name": "Cognitive Capitalism",
